{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17651761","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17651761"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:27:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:27:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18492"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18492","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18492"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.16,0.26,0.45,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11221"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76762"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11221","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11221"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18492"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62255"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6973"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26044"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26269"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26327"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76762"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pancreas requires a rich blood supply to support both its exocrine and endocrine functions. Multiple arterial vessels contribute to its blood supply.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following arteries provides the main blood supply to the body and tail of the pancreas?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Common hepatic","Gastroduodenal","Inferior pancreaticoduodenal","Splenic","Superior mesenteric"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esplenic artery\u003C/strong\u003E (image) is the main arterial supply to the body and tail of the pancreas via its pancreatic branches. These branches run within the substance of the pancreas as they course along the organ.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are incorrect because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Egastroduodenal artery\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the head of the pancreas via its superior pancreaticoduodenal branches\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior mesenteric artery\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the head of the pancreas via inferior pancreaticoduodenal branches\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecommon hepatic artery\u003C/strong\u003E does not directly supply the pancreas but gives rise to the gastroduodenal artery\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einferior pancreaticoduodenal artery\u003C/strong\u003E arises from the superior mesenteric artery and supplies only the head of the pancreas\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe arterial supply to the pancreas forms a complex network of anastomoses between branches of the coeliac trunk and superior mesenteric artery, ensuring adequate blood flow throughout the organ.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The pancreas receives arterial blood supply from branches of both the coeliac trunk and superior mesenteric artery.","The splenic artery gives rise to multiple pancreatic branches that supply the body and tail of the pancreas.","The pancreaticoduodenal arteries form anterior and posterior arcades around the head of the pancreas, creating important anastomoses between the coeliac trunk and superior mesenteric artery."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cCeliac Trunk and Branches\u201d by Dennis M DePace, PhD is licensed under\u00a0Creative Commons\u00a0Attribution-Share Alike 4.0 Unported\u00a0license. (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0). \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Celiac_Trunk_and_Branches.jpg\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62255"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18492"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21397"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21397","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21397"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/hb8OiZQaOkSG1BnuA1flWs7hPg4xCn.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/hb8OiZQaOkSG1BnuA1flWs7hPg4xCn.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":491}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62255","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62255"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T08:26:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T08:26:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11221"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76762"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"he